ormality; and in Day by Day, Robert Lowell subtracts from plenitude. In Geography III, Elizabeth Bishop is both caught and freed, while James Merrill, in A Scattering of Salts, creates a series of self-portraits as he dies, representing himself by such things as a Christmas tree, human tissue on a laboratory slide, and the evening/morning star. The solution for one poet will not serve for another; each must invent a bridge from an old style to a new one. Casting a last look at life as they contemplate death, these modern writers enrich the resources of lyric poetry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAmerican poetryx20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDeath in literature. 0aLITERARY CRITICISMvPoetry. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAdjective.  aAfter Apple-Picking.  aAllusion.  aAmputation.  aArs Poetica (Horace).  aAsymmetry.  aBecause I could not stop for Death.  aBevel.  aBinocular vision.  aBluebeard's Castle.  aBurial.  aCalcium carbonate.  aCarbon monoxide.  aCaspar David Friedrich.  aCoffin.  aCouplet.  aDeath and Life.  aDeath drive.  aDeath.  aDeathbed.  aDesiccation.  aDiction.  aDisjecta membra.  aDramatis Personae.  aElizabeth Bishop.  aEmblem.  aEmily Dickinson.  aEmptiness.  aExecutive director.  aEzra Pound.  aFairy tale.  aFine art.  aGrandparent.  aHexameter.  aHuman extinction.  aImpermanence.  aIn Death.  aIn the Flesh (TV series).  aIncineration.  aIrony.  aJames Merrill.  aJohn Donne.  aJohn Keats.  aLady Lazarus.  aLament.  aLast Poems.  aLecture.  aLife Studies.  aLycidas.  aMacabre.  aMelodrama.  aMetaphor.  aMicrotome.  aMisery (novel).  aMourning.  aNarcissism.  aNarrative.  aNational Gallery of Art.  aN